  • Classes 
    Class Description
    com.google.mu.util.stream.Cases
    Use findFirstElements() and/or findOnlyElements() methods together with Optional.or(java.util.function.Supplier<? extends java.util.Optional<? extends T>>) instead.
  • Methods 
    Method Description
    com.google.mu.util.BiOptional.both​(Optional<A>, Optional<B>)
    Use Optionals.both(java.util.Optional<? extends A>, java.util.Optional<? extends B>) instead.
    com.google.mu.util.Optionals.flatMapBoth​(Optional<A>, Optional<B>, CheckedBiFunction<? super A, ? super B, ? extends Optional<R>, E>)
    Use Optionals.both(java.util.Optional<? extends A>, java.util.Optional<? extends B>) instead.
    com.google.mu.util.Optionals.mapBoth​(Optional<A>, Optional<B>, CheckedBiFunction<? super A, ? super B, ? extends R, E>)
    Use Optionals.both(java.util.Optional<? extends A>, java.util.Optional<? extends B>) instead.
    com.google.mu.util.stream.BiStream.from​(Collection<T>, Function<? super T, ? extends K>, Function<? super T, ? extends V>)
    Use biStream(User::id, users) to create BiStream<UserId, User>, or, use biStream(users, User::getAccount) to create BiStream<User, Account>. Then use BiStream.mapKeys(java.util.function.BiFunction<? super K, ? super V, ? extends K2>) or BiStream.mapValues(java.util.function.BiFunction<? super K, ? super V, ? extends V2>) to apply further mappings.
    com.google.mu.util.stream.Cases.switching​(Collector<? super T, ?, ? extends Optional<? extends R>>...)
    Use Cases.cases(java.util.stream.Collector<? super T, ?, ? extends java.util.Optional<? extends R>>...) instead.
    com.google.mu.util.Substring.Pattern.not()
    Use Substring.Pattern.notFollowedBy(java.lang.String) or Substring.Pattern.notImmediatelyBetween(java.lang.String, java.lang.String) for negative lookahead and negative lookbehind.
    com.google.mu.util.Substring.Pattern.peek​(String)
    Use Substring.Pattern.followedBy(java.lang.String) instead.
    com.google.mu.util.Substring.Pattern.withBoundary​(CharPredicate)
    Use Substring.Pattern.separatedBy(CharPredicate) instead.
